description._content: www.theedinburghblog.co.uk - review coming soon

I took my new D90 out to the bar to try it out in low light and I don't think I could have been much happier. It is a huge step up from the D40. Even Gemma commented on the clarity of the pictures and she was amazed that I could take photos when it was so dark.

On top of serving fantastic food and drinks this restaurant was a visual delight for photography. I picked out Gemma's reflection on the mirror. She is has a slight motion blur but this was the best expression of the moments I captured of her in the mirror.
I can't remember if this was the food menu, cocktail list, or wine list but needless to say there was a great range of choices for all of the above.
I spotted this guy in the restaurant where we were eating. Not sure if he had been having a business dinner but I wanted to test the low light performance of my new D90 and it did not disappoint.

title._content: At the Dome with Mummy and Andrew

description._content: close up of some of the folks enjoying drinking and eating outside on the lovely, warm, spring day. Quite right - never know how quickly such weather will vanish again in Scotland (a week after I took this it was snowing again! After a week of record temperatures for March, back to winter! Ah, Scotland...)

rather splendid old building down by the Shore area of Leith which is a nicely regenerated area full of bars and restaurants on the side of the Water of Leith, ground floor now a large restaurant and bar, rather popular on this warm, spring day as you can see

Low quality shot as this was a quick snap through the window at an angle from the top of a double decker bus, but as it was stopped outside Illegal Jack's on Lothian Road I could see the lettering on the window being hit by the sun and casting distinct shadows onto the shaved parts of this diner's scalp and had to try and grab a quick shot even through the window distortions.
